question: What is the time complexity of binary search?
explanation: Binary search has O(log n) time complexity because it divides the search space in half with each iteration.

question: Which data structure follows LIFO principle?
explanation: Stack follows LIFO (Last In, First Out) principle where the last element added is the first one to be removed.

question: What is the worst-case time complexity of quicksort?
explanation: Quicksort has O(n²) worst-case time complexity when the pivot is always the smallest or largest element.

question: What is the space complexity of merge sort?
explanation: Merge sort requires O(n) additional space to store the merged subarrays during the sorting process.

question: What is the time complexity of inserting an element at the beginning of an array?
explanation: Inserting at the beginning requires shifting all existing elements, which takes O(n) time.

question: What is the time complexity of accessing an element in a hash table?
explanation: Hash table provides average O(1) time complexity for access operations.

question: What is the time complexity of finding the minimum element in a binary search tree?
explanation: Finding minimum requires traversing to the leftmost node, which takes O(log n) time in a balanced tree.

question: What is the space complexity of recursive binary search?
explanation: Recursive binary search uses O(log n) space due to the call stack depth.

question: What is the time complexity of bubble sort?
explanation: Bubble sort has O(n²) time complexity due to nested loops comparing adjacent elements.

question: What is the time complexity of depth-first search on a graph?
explanation: DFS visits each vertex and edge at most once, giving O(V + E) time complexity.
